  "text": "The Envoy hot restart mechanism is implemented across multiple C++ source files in envoyproxy/envoy. The core abstraction is the HotRestart interface defined in envoy/server/hot_restart.h, which specifies methods for drainParentListeners(), duplicateParentListenSocket(), sendParentAdminShutdownRequest(), mergeParentStatsIfAny(), and other operations for coordinating hot restarts between parent and child processes.\n\nThe primary implementation is HotRestartImpl (source/server/hot_restart_impl.h and .cc), which manages shared memory via attachSharedMemory() and initializeMutex() functions. The shared memory structure maintains version information, process-shared mutexes for logging, and synchronization flags (SHMEM_FLAGS_INITIALIZING). HotRestartImpl delegates actual protocol handling to two collaborators: HotRestartingChild and HotRestartingParent.\n\nThe parent/child process handshake and socket passing are implemented through the RpcStream class (source/server/hot_restarting_base.h and .cc), which manages Unix domain socket communication using an ad-hoc RPC protocol. Messages are sent via sendHotRestartMessage(), which uses sendmsg() with SCM_RIGHTS ancillary data to pass file descriptors between processes. Received messages are processed by receiveHotRestartMessage(), with getPassedFdIfPresent() extracting file descriptors from control data.\n\nThe HotRestartingParent class (source/server/hot_restarting_parent.h and .cc) listens on domain sockets for requests from child processes. Its Internal class handles specific requests: shutdownAdmin() coordinates admin shutdown, getListenSocketsForChild() passes listening sockets with file descriptors to the child process, exportStatsToChild() serializes parent stats, and drainListeners() initiates the drain sequence.\n\nThe HotRestartingChild class (source/server/hot_restarting_child.cc and .h) implements child-side logic, with duplicateParentListenSocket() requesting socket duplication from parent, drainParentListeners() signaling the child is ready, registerParentDrainedCallback() registering callbacks for when parent draining completes, and UdpForwardingContext managing UDP listener registration for QUIC packet forwarding during drain.\n\nMessage serialization uses Protocol Buffers defined in source/server/hot_restart.proto, which specifies HotRestartMessage with Request and Reply variants for PassListenSocket, ShutdownAdmin, Stats, DrainListeners, Terminate, and ForwardedUdpPacket operations. Two separate RPC streams (main_rpc_stream_ and udp_forwarding_rpc_stream_) ensure UDP forwarding packets don't interfere with control messages.\n\nOS-level socket operations are abstracted through HotRestartOsSysCalls (envoy/api/os_sys_calls_hot_restart.h) with POSIX implementation in source/common/api/posix/os_sys_calls_impl_hot_restart.cc, providing shm_open() and shm_unlink() for shared memory management. ProcessSharedMutex wraps pthread_mutex with PTHREAD_PROCESS_SHARED attributes for cross-process synchronization.\n\nThe hot restart mechanism supports graceful drain sequences where the parent process receives drain requests, the child waits for parent readiness signals via registered callbacks, and UDP packets destined for the child are forwarded during the drain window through the separate UDP forwarding channel."
}

